But a separate study suggests a rise in interest rates could leave one million homeowners in danger of defaulting on their mortgages and other debts.

Citizens Advice has warned of a ‘financial ticking timebomb’ if there is even a modest rise in interest rates.

Chief executive Gillian Guy said: ‘The rising cost of energy, food and travel has been absorbing any spare income people may have. In some cases there is little or nothing left to cope with larger mortgage repayments.’

Even if rates rise gently from 0.5 per cent to 3 per cent by 2018, 1.12million would spend most of their take-home pay on debt repayments, said the Resolution Foundation think-tank.

